  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">DRC Ebola outbreak 2018</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">9th Ebola epidemic outbreak in DRC in the Equateur region. Bikoro and Mbandaka city affected this is the hub for regional exchanges in proximity to CAR and Republic of Congo. A week after this was declared over DRC were confronted with a 10th outbreak in North Kivu Province. On 1 August 2018 the Ministry of Health of the Democratic Republic of the Congo notified WHO of a new outbreak of Ebola virus disease (EVD) in North Kivu Province in the eastern part of the country. The province of North Kivu is among the most populated provinces with eight million inhabitants. It shares borders with four other provinces (Ituri South Kivu Maniema and Tshopo) as well as with Uganda and Rwanda. (There is a tangible risk of EVD transmission in Uganda and Rwanda). The sub-region has been experiencing intense insecurity and worsening humanitarian crisis with over one million internally displaced people and a continuous efflux of refugees to the neighbouring countries including Uganda Burundi and Tanzania. The protracted conflict context makes the emergency response activities more difficult because of restrained access and security risks. The EVD outbreak is rapidly evolving with more new confirmed cases and deaths occurring. WHO regional risk raised to HIGH. Category of emergency (IFRC): RED RC launched a One International Appeal in May 18 fundraising for all RC components involved in the response (including ICRC). Appeal has been expanded several times incorporating the response in Equateur Eastern DRC and in all neighboring Priority 1 countries (Rwanda Burundi S.Sudan and Uganda).</narrative>
  </description>
